The equivalent width measures the amount of energy removed from the continuum.  W is an incredibly complex measurement: it encodes information on the column density, the velocity distribution, and the covering fraction of the gas. This makes the interpretation of W difficult. First we explore how W scales with host galaxy properties, and then we study what drives this evolution.

The W scaling relations with {$M_\ast$ } are presented in \autoref{fig:ewm}. For {Si~{\sc II}~}~1260~\AA, {Si~{\sc III}~}~1206~\AA, and {Si~{\sc IV}~}~1393~\AA\ the relations are strong with 3.6, 4.1 and 3.8$\sigma$ significance levels. The higher significance level for the {Si~{\sc III}~} transition versus the {Si~{\sc IV}~} transition is because the {Si~{\sc III}~} transition has a larger dynamic range that extends down to log({$M_\ast$}/M$_\odot$) of 7.5, while the lowest mass {Si~{\sc IV}~} galaxy is 8.96. {Si~{\sc IV}~} is a weaker transition, and only {Si~{\sc II}~} and {Si~{\sc III}~} are detected in the lower mass galaxies. There are two marginally detected low-mass galaxies (greater than 1$\sigma$ but less than 3$\sigma$) that increase the significance level of the {Si~{\sc IV}~} W-{$M_\ast$ } trend to 4.3$\sigma$. The three significant Si relations are given as:

The normalizations in \autoref{eq:wrelations} go from highest to lowest for {Si~{\sc III}}, {Si~{\sc II}}, and {Si~{\sc IV}}, qualitatively consistent with the trend of W estimations given in \autoref{tab:detection}. However, quantitatively they are quite different than calculated in \autoref{tab:detection}. The differences show that both the strength of the line and the fraction of gas in each transition (the ionization fraction) determines the equivalent width ratios. In \autoref{ionize} we explore the mechanisms that determine the ionization fractions.

We also study how W varies with SFR, and gas phase metallicity. The SFR trends are similar to the {$M_\ast$ } trends (see \autoref{tab:ewsfr}), but the significances are lower for the {O~{\sc I}~} and {Si~{\sc II}~} transitions. Additionally, the gas phase metallicity is known to vary with {$M_\ast$ } (the \lq\lq{}mass-metallicity relation\rq\rq{}; \citealp{tremonti04, andrews13}), and this relationship might be a natural driver of the W-{$M_\ast$ } (and SFR) relationships. We use the gas-phase metallicities from the literature (see Paper {\sc I}) to find that the correlation between the {Si~{\sc IV}~} W and gas phase metallicity is weaker than for {$M_\ast$ } alone (2.8$\sigma$ for the metallicity and 3.7$\sigma$ for {$M_\ast$}).

The interpretation of W is difficult because it has complicated degeneracies. A large W can indicate a high column density gas distributed over a small velocity range, or a low column density of gas widely distributed in velocity space.  Additionally, W will depend on the fraction of the source covered by the outflow (where the uncovered part of the source decreases W). This leads to a complicated triple degeneracy with column density, velocity distribution, and covering fraction. Below, we use the {Si~{\sc IV}~} doublet to explore what drives the observed relation between W and {$M_\ast$ }. We use {Si~{\sc IV}~} because the equivalent width is strongly correlated with {$M_\ast$ } and SFR, while the doublet allows for calculation of the covering fraction (C$_f$; \autoref{eq:cf}), the line center optical depth ($\tau_0$; \autoref{eq:taucf}), and the velocity width ($\Delta$; \autoref{eq:b}), which we cannot measure with the {Si~{\sc III}~} singlet. We can then determine the primary driver of the shallow  W trends with {$M_\ast$}.

The upper right panel of \autoref{fig:doublet} shows a flat distribution of $\tau_0$ with {$M_\ast$ } (\autoref{tab:si4relations}). There are two mergers and one spiral with optical depths substantially lower than the rest of the galaxies (NGC~3256 has an optical depth less than one), but the rest of the transitions are optically thick. The median $\tau_0$ is 2.55, with a range from 0.97 to 3.3. The optical depths indicate that the lines are moderately saturated, and the optical depth will not drive strong evolution in W. 

