The normalizations in \autoref{eq:wrelations} go from highest to lowest for {Si~{\sc III}}, {Si~{\sc II}}, and {Si~{\sc IV}}, qualitatively consistent with the trend of W estimations given in \autoref{tab:detection}. However, quantitatively they are quite different than calculated in \autoref{tab:detection}. The differences show that both the strength of the line and the fraction of gas in each transition (the ionization fraction) determines the equivalent width ratios. In \autoref{ionize} we explore the mechanisms that determine the ionization fractions.

We also study how W varies with SFR, and gas phase metallicity. The SFR trends are similar to the {$M_\ast$ } trends (see \autoref{tab:ewsfr}), but the significances are lower for the {O~{\sc I}~} and {Si~{\sc II}~} transitions. Additionally, the gas phase metallicity is known to vary with {$M_\ast$ } (the \lq\lq{}mass-metallicity relation\rq\rq{}; \citealp{tremonti04, andrews13}), and this relationship might be a natural driver of the W-{$M_\ast$ } (and SFR) relationships. We use the gas-phase metallicities from the literature (see Paper {\sc I}) to find that the correlation between the {Si~{\sc IV}~} W and gas phase metallicity is weaker than for {$M_\ast$ } alone (2.8$\sigma$ for the metallicity and 3.7$\sigma$ for {$M_\ast$}).

The interpretation of W is difficult because it has complicated degeneracies. A large W can indicate a high column density gas distributed over a small velocity range, or a low column density of gas widely distributed in velocity space.  Additionally, W will depend on the fraction of the source covered by the outflow (where the uncovered part of the source decreases W). This leads to a complicated triple degeneracy with column density, velocity distribution, and covering fraction. Below, we use the {Si~{\sc IV}~} doublet to explore what drives the observed relation between W and {$M_\ast$ }. We use {Si~{\sc IV}~} because the equivalent width is strongly correlated with {$M_\ast$ } and SFR, while the doublet allows for calculation of the covering fraction (C$_f$; \autoref{eq:cf}), the line center optical depth ($\tau_0$; \autoref{eq:taucf}), and the velocity width ($\Delta$; \autoref{eq:b}), which we cannot measure with the {Si~{\sc III}~} singlet. We can then determine the primary driver of the shallow  W trends with {$M_\ast$}.

The upper right panel of \autoref{fig:doublet} shows a flat distribution of $\tau_0$ with {$M_\ast$ } (\autoref{tab:si4relations}). There are two mergers and one spiral with optical depths substantially lower than the rest of the galaxies (NGC~3256 has an optical depth less than one), but the rest of the transitions are optically thick. The median $\tau_0$ is 2.55, with a range from 0.97 to 3.3. The optical depths indicate that the lines are moderately saturated, and the optical depth will not drive strong evolution in W. 

\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[width = 0.5\textwidth]{f6.pdf}
\caption{Product of the line width ($\Delta$) and the covering fraction (C$_f$) versus the equivalent width (W) of the {Si~{\sc IV}~} 1393~\AA\ line. For moderately saturated lines, the equivalent width is approximately equal to this product. The strong, nearly linear, correlation shows that $\Delta$ times C$_f$ accounts for 85\% of the variation of W. }
\label{fig:cfdel}
\end{figure}

For a moderately optically thick line, W is the product of $\Delta$ and C$_f$. This relationship is shown in \autoref{fig:cfdel}, where a tight (scatter of 4~{km~s$^{ -1}$}) and strong (6$\sigma$, $\tau_K$ = 0.75, and R$^2$ = 0.85) relationship describes 85\% of the variation of W. Therefore, either $\Delta$, C$_f$, or the product of the two drives the observed relationship between {$M_\ast$ } and W.

The lower left panel of \autoref{fig:doublet} shows the distribution of the line center C$_f$ with {$M_\ast$}. A nearly constant relationship is seen, with a median value of 0.82. The null correlation with {$M_\ast$ } (0.45$\sigma$) is also seen with the relationship between C$_f$ and W, which has a $\tau_K$ of 0.02 and a significance level of 0.18$\sigma$. Therefore,  C$_f$ does not drive the W values.  The non-unity C$_f$ may arise from emission line infilling of resonantly scattered emission lines \citep{prochaska2011, martin12, rubin13, guantun}. However, we only observe Si~{\sc II$^\ast$} emission lines in a small subset of our spectra  (all at higher redshifts), and we conclude that Si~{\sc II} resonant emission does not substantially effect the measured C$_f$, or line profiles. The degraded spectral resolution from the COS line-spread function and extended light distribution could contribute to the non-unity covering fraction \citep{prochaska2011}. 

Finally, the lower right panel of \autoref{fig:doublet} shows the scaling of $\Delta$ with {$M_\ast$}. A 3.6$\sigma$ relationship is seen between log($\Delta$) and log({$M_\ast$}/M$_\odot$) with a scaling of (see \autoref{tab:si4relations}):


The relation is fairly tight (15~{km~s$^{ -1}$}) until log({$M_\ast$}/M$_\odot$) of 10.5, where three mergers and two compact galaxies increase the scatter. Furthermore, $\Delta$ and W are strongly correlated with a 5.0$\sigma$ significance, $\tau_K$ of 0.63, and an R$^2$ of 0.70. The {$M_\ast$ } exponent is consistent with the exponent of the W relations, and indicates that the line width (as measured by $\Delta$) drives the variation between W and {$M_\ast$}.

In summary, there are shallow, but highly significant, trends between W and {$M_\ast$ } for the {Si~{\sc II}~}~1260~\AA, {Si~{\sc III}~}~1206~\AA\, and {Si~{\sc IV}~}~1393~\AA\ transitions. The SFR has similar trends as {$M_\ast$}. A larger sample with a range of SFR at constant {$M_\ast$ } is needed to determine the primary driver of the trends. For the {Si~{\sc IV}~} relations, $\Delta$ is primarily responsible for increasing W, such that larger W corresponds to larger $\Delta$. 

